ilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1318–1367":"circa 1318–1367","1318–1367":"1318–1367","1318–1377":"1318–1377","1367–1381":"1367–1381","1313–1347":"1313–1347","1328–1391":"1328–1391","1340":"1340","1381":"1381","1391":"1391","1337":"1337","about 1318":"circa 1318","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1367":"1367","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","about 1366":"circa 1366","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Stow, Lincolnshire, England":"Stow, Lincolnshire, England","Stowe House, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Stowe House, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1318–1367":"about 1318–1367","1318–1367":"1318–1367","1318–1377":"1318–1377","1367–1381":"1367–1381","1313–1347":"1313–1347","1328–1391":"1328–1391","1340":"1340","1381":"1381","1391":"1391","1337":"1337","about 1318":"about 1318","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1367":"1367","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","about 1366":"about 1366","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Stow, Lincolnshire, England":"Stow, Lincolnshire, England","Stowe House, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Stowe House, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":10,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":19,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Joyce de Beaumont was born about 1318, in Stow, Lincolnshire, England, her father, Thomas de Beaumont, was 6 and her mother, Eleanor de Beauchamp, was -9. She married Sir Theobald de Grenville I about 1366, in Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1367, in Cornwall, England, at the age of 50, and was buried in Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England."},"et":{"about 1318–1367":"umbes 1318–1367","1318–1367":"1318–1367","1318–1377":"1318–1377","1367–1381":"1367–1381","1313–1347":"1313–1347","1328–1391":"1328–1391","1340":"1340","1381":"1381","1391":"1391","1337":"1337","about 1318":"umbes 1318","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1367":"1367","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","about 1366":"umbes 1366","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Stow, Lincolnshire, England":"Stow, Lincolnshire, England","Stowe House, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Stowe House, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1318–1367":"noin 1318–1367","1318–1367":"1318–1367","1318–1377":"1318–1377","1367–1381":"1367–1381","1313–1347":"1313–1347","1328–1391":"1328–1391","1340":"1340","1381":"1381","1391":"1391","1337":"1337","about 1318":"noin 1318","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1367":"1367","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","about 1366":"noin 1366","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Stow, Lincolnshire, England":"Stow, Lincolnshire, England","Stowe House, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Stowe House, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"De